3. Internal Business Use

Internal business use is permitted without charge. This includes employees
using the Software to access accounting, ERP, CRM, RPA, intranet, call-center,
or other business systems and organizations using the Software to support
revenue-generating operations unrelated to commercializing the Software
itself.

The Software may be used on company-owned or company-controlled computers,
servers, virtual machines, Cloud PCs, and remote desktops. A business may earn
revenue from its normal operations while using the Software internally.

4. Permitted Managed, Hosted, and Operational Services

A service provider may install and operate an unmodified Official Binary in an
RPA, VDI, Cloud PC, virtual machine, Remote Desktop, hosted desktop, SaaS, or
managed operational environment and may allow its customers to access and use
the Software remotely, provided that the service does not have Primary
Software Value.

A provider may charge for the overall value of a broader service, including:

- RPA design and operation;
- infrastructure, servers, hosting, VDI, Cloud PC, or remote access;
- automation workflows and business-process operation;
- system integration, monitoring, security, backup, and compliance; and
- support and maintenance of the provider's broader environment.

Installing, configuring, updating, monitoring, or providing ordinary
Software-specific assistance is permitted when it is incidental to such a
broader service and is not separately priced, separately marketed, or used to
increase the service price because the Software is included.

A provider may not charge a separate, additional, itemized, per-user,
per-Workspace, per-Tab, per-installation, subscription, support-tier, training,
or license fee for the Software. A provider also may not describe a broader
service fee as infrastructure or managed-service revenue when the service in
substance has Primary Software Value.

Examples of permitted services include an RPA provider using the Software as
one operational tool in a wider automation solution, or a VDI provider making
the Software available within a managed desktop whose primary value is the
desktop and infrastructure service.

This Section does not permit using source code or a Derivative Work to build a
commercial service, rebranding the Software, or offering a service whose main
commercial value is access to the Software's Workspace, Tab, WebView, or
browser-management functionality.

5. Source-Code Forks and Modifications

You may fork and modify the source code for personal, educational, research,
internal business, and non-commercial community purposes.

When redistributing original or modified source code, you must:

- include a complete copy of this License;
- preserve all copyright, attribution, licensing, and third-party notices;
- clearly identify the work as modified from Edge Workspace Manager;
- describe the material modifications made;
- use a name that does not imply that the modified version is an Official
  release;
- not use the Licensor's name, project name, branding, or logos in a manner
  that suggests endorsement, sponsorship, certification, or affiliation; and
- distribute the source code under this same License without adding terms that
  reduce or conflict with this License.

Permission to distribute source code does not include permission to distribute
compiled binaries, installers, ZIP packages, or update manifests.

6. Official Binaries and Distribution

Official Binaries may be downloaded and installed from an Official
Distribution Channel. You may share links that direct users to an Official
Distribution Channel.

Unless you have prior written permission from the Licensor, you may not:

- re-upload, mirror, host, cache for public distribution, or redistribute an
  Official Binary;
- make an Official Binary available for download from another website,
  repository, file-sharing service, application store, server, or content
  delivery network;
- repackage, rename, wrap, modify, or digitally re-sign an Official Binary;
- publish a modified or replacement update manifest;
- represent a third-party download as an Official Distribution Channel; or
- distribute compiled binaries created from a Derivative Work.

Installing an Official Binary in an environment operated for an authorized
customer under Section 4 is permitted and is not public redistribution,
provided that the installer or binary is not separately made available for
download or copying.

7. Bundling with Other Products

The Software may be offered as a free, optional companion to another product
or service by providing a link to an Official Distribution Channel. No portion
of the price of the other product or service may be attributed to the Software.

An Official Binary may not be included directly inside another downloadable
package, installer, product bundle, application-store listing, or hosted file
without prior written permission from the Licensor.

The other product or service must not depend primarily on the Software for its
commercial value, claim ownership of the Software, rebrand the Software,
suggest endorsement by the Licensor, or remove or alter any legal notice.

8. Prohibited Software-Centric Commercial Uses

Without a separate written commercial license from the Licensor, you may not:

- sell, license, sublicense, rent, lease, or commercially distribute the
  Software or any Derivative Work;
- sell access to a modified, forked, rebranded, or source-derived version of
  the Software;
- offer a product, subscription, hosted application, SaaS, PaaS, managed
  service, or support service that has Primary Software Value;
- use source code to create a paid Browser Workspace, Tab Management, WebView
  workspace, hosted application, subscription service, or managed software
  product;
- incorporate source code or a Derivative Work into a commercial product or
  service;
- expose source-derived functionality through an API, website, desktop
  application, mobile application, automation platform, or other paid service;
- separately sell or market Software installation, configuration, maintenance,
  support, or training;
- calculate or increase a fee based on Software users, Workspaces, Tabs,
  installations, usage, support, maintenance, or training;
- disguise a Software-related fee as part of another mandatory purchase,
  subscription, infrastructure charge, managed-service charge, or contract; or
- falsely imply ownership, endorsement, sponsorship, or affiliation.

This Section does not prohibit internal business use or the incidental use and
assistance expressly permitted under Sections 3 and 4.

